jan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Kelly","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Kieran, Aileen, John Patrick, Siobhan, Liam, Brigid, Donovan, Eamon, Parnell, Aidan, Clancy.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Ceallaigh</b>, or, in some areas, <b>Mac Ceallaigh</b> ‘descendant (or son) of <i>Ceallach</i>’, an ancient Irish personal name, originally a byname meaning ‘bright-headed’, later understood as ‘frequenting churches’ (Irish <i>ceall</i>). There are several early Irish saints who bore this name. <i>Kelly</i> is now the most common of all surnames in Ireland.","Scottish: habitational name from either the lands of Kelly, near Arbroath (Angus), Kellie in Carnbee (Fife), or Kelly in Methlick (Aberdeenshire). Each of these placenames is from Pictish <i>celli</i> or Gaelic <i>coille</i> ‘wood’ + the placename forming suffix <i>-in</i>. Alternatively, from the lands of Kelloe in the barony of Hume (Berwickshire), whose name is of uncertain origin."],"variants":[{"name":"Kelley","meanings":["Irish (Offaly) and English: variant of   Kelly  ."]},{"name":"Kilkelly","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Bridie.","Irish (Galway): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Giolla Ceallaigh</b> ‘son of the devotee of (Saint) Ceallach’ (see   Kelly  )."]},{"name":"Killeen","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Donovan, Kieran, Liam.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Cillín</b> ‘descendant of <i>Cillín</i>’, a pet form of the personal name <i>Ceallach</i> (see   Kelly  ). The name was borne by various early Irish saints, including the leader of a 7th-century mission to Franconia and Thuringia, hence the popularity of the personal name   Kilian   in medieval central Europe."]},{"name":"Kellis","meanings":["Scottish: patronymic based on   Kelly   as a personal name. Compare   Kellison  .","Greek: descriptive nickname for a bald man, from <i>kelis</i> ‘bald’, a word of Turkish origin (from <i>kel</i> ‘bald’).","History: As a surname of Scottish origin, this has been established in NC since the 18th century."]},{"name":"Kellie","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Kelly  ."]},{"name":"Kellison","meanings":["Scottish: patronymic based on   Kelly   as a personal name."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":22,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":35,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":44,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When John de Kelly was born in 1293, in Exeter, Devon, England, his father, John de Kelly, was 70 and his mother, Dionysia de Siccavilla, was 23.